{"id":"2006.12327","submitter":"Shana Moothedath","authors":"Shana Moothedath, Dinuka Sahabandu, Joey Allen, Andrew Clark, Linda\n  Bushnell, Wenke Lee, and Radha Poovendran","title":"Dynamic Information Flow Tracking for Detection of Advanced Persistent\n  Threats: A Stochastic Game Approach","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.GT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Advanced Persistent Threats (APTs) are stealthy customized attacks by\nintelligent adversaries. This paper deals with the detection of APTs that\ninfiltrate cyber systems and compromise specifically targeted data and/or\ninfrastructures. Dynamic information flow tracking is an information\ntrace-based detection mechanism against APTs that taints suspicious information\nflows in the system and generates security analysis for unauthorized use of\ntainted data. In this paper, we develop an analytical model for\nresource-efficient detection of APTs using an information flow tracking game.\nThe game is a nonzero-sum, turn-based, stochastic game with asymmetric\ninformation as the defender cannot distinguish whether an incoming flow is\nmalicious or benign and hence has only partial state observation. We analyze\nequilibrium of the game and prove that a Nash equilibrium is given by a\nsolution to the minimum capacity cut set problem on a flow-network derived from\nthe system, where the edge capacities are obtained from the cost of performing\nsecurity analysis. Finally, we implement our algorithm on the real-world\ndataset for a data exfiltration attack augmented with false-negative and\nfalse-positive rates and compute an optimal defender strategy.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 22 Jun 2020 15:12:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 25 Jun 2021 23:28:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-06-29"}
