{"id":"2006.12331","submitter":"Charis Anastopoulos","authors":"Nikolaos Papadatos and Charis Anastopoulos","title":"Relativistic Quantum Thermodynamics of Moving Systems","comments":"24 pages, 4 figures; minor changes, references added, to appear in\n  PRD","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. D 102, 085005 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.102.085005","report-no":"University of Patras, 26500 Patras","categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.stat-mech gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We analyse the thermodynamics of a quantum system in a trajectory of constant\nvelocity that interacts with a static thermal bath. The latter is modeled by a\nmassless scalar field in a thermal state. We consider two different couplings\nof the moving system to the heat bath, a coupling of the Unruh-DeWitt type and\na coupling that involves the time derivative of the field. We derive the master\nequation for the reduced dynamics of the moving quantum system. It has the same\nform with the quantum optical master equation, but with different coefficients\nthat depend on velocity. This master equation has a unique asymptotic state for\neach type of coupling, and it is characterized by a well-defined notion of\nheat-flow. Our analysis of the second law of thermodynamics leads to a\nsurprising equivalence: a moving heat bath is physically equivalent to a\nmixture of heat baths at rest, each with a different temperature. There is no\nunique rule for the Lorentz transformation of temperature. We propose that\nLorentz transformations of thermodynamic states are well defined in an extended\nthermodynamic space that is obtained as a convex hull of the standard\nthermodynamic space.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 22 Jun 2020 15:18:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 4 Oct 2020 18:19:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-10-14"}
